<p><b>South African Sign Language</b> is the primary language used by the Deaf community in <a href="/wiki/South_Africa" title="South Africa">South Africa</a>. Although there is no official figure, most of the 12,000 Deaf South Africans understand SASL to some degree.</p>
<p>South African Sign Language is not one of South Africa's 11 <a href="/wiki/Official_language" title="Official language">official languages</a> but it has gained "constitutional and legal protection in the South African context"<sup id="cite_ref-SASLeducation_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SASLeducation-0"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> thanks to the <a href="/wiki/Constitution_of_the_Republic_of_South_Africa" title="Constitution of the Republic of South Africa" class="mw-redirect">Constitution of the Republic of South Africa</a> which encourages the "development and promotion of sign language", and thanks to national educational policies<sup id="cite_ref-SASLeducation_0-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SASLeducation-0"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-1996SAschoolAct_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1996SAschoolAct-1"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup>.</p>
